Photoluminescence spectra of aqueous solution of carbon dot sample were recorded at different excitation wavelengths in the range of 350−700 nm (Fig. 5
                        ). The highest fluorescence intensity was recorded at 462 nm (λem) in the emission spectra with the excitation of carbon quantum dots at 376 nm (λex). Thus, the carbon quantum dot sample showed the turquoise color in UV cabine using 365 nm lamp (Fig. 6
                        ). Besides, the same fluorescence color was detected in the color map (Fig. 7
                        ). While the excitation wavelengths increased, the emission wavelengths increased. The excitation wavelength leads different emission spectrum. By changing excitation wavelength, the resulting emission color can tune to desired one. This tunable color spectrum possibly originated from two main factors as debated in the literature (Sharma et al., 2016; van Dam et al., 2017; Zhao et al., 2019). Both carbon core and supported functional groups such as CO and COOH, exhibit excitation dependent photoluminescence properties. Additionally, uniform and non-uniform sized CDs show the excitation dependent PL properties in the mechanism (Cheng et al., 2019; Murugan et al., 2019; Pathak et al., 2019; Pourreza and Ghomi, 2019; Sharma et al., 2016; van Dam et al., 2017). Thus, the mechanism of excitation dependent PL is related to chemical compositions of carbon core and the supported functional groups on it. The localized energy levels caused by the size effect of the sp2 clusters due to the aromatic and oxidized carbonic structures mainly responsible from low wavelength emissions. CO and COOH groups over and edge of CDs also having aromatic π-electrons induce the electrostatic interaction, non-radiative recombination of excitations through electron transfer between the substituents of CDs. The defect states of the CQDs causes blue emission (Gan et al., 2016).

Upon proving the potential of the C-dot in fluorescent cell imaging, we aimed at measuring its effect on cell growth in order to understand its usability in long term experiments. For this purpose, H2452 mesothelioma cells were plated and treated with the two concentrations used for cell imaging. For calculating the changing confluence of the cells in the pictures taken at 0, 24, 48 and 72 h (Fig. 9
                           ), image analysis software of Juli Br microscope was used. The values were plotted in Graph Pad and statistical analyses were performed (Fig. 10
                           ).

In order to address the second possibility, that is, the CDs could be cytotoxic to all types of human cells, we repeated MTS assay with a healthy human cell line, HUVEC under similar conditions. As it was revealed in Fig. 12
                           ., CDs were able to kill healthy human cells at the same concentrations (Fig. 13
                           ).
